Text: They say that the road to hell is paved with good intentions, and I feel like the same can be said about the road to deployment.
But I'll save the best for last.

This week's exceed expectations for sure, as we didn't just manage to have a back-end up and running in the cloud, we even found Jupyter notebook to be a perfect place for us to present out report for Rodney.
He can even access it at a click without the overhead of cloning a Github repo and further troublesome installation.
Everything feels almost too smooth to be true after all the troubles we went through with Cassandra.

Another wonderful but rather belated piece of good news is that Rodney has agreed to set us up with three of his customers, who are teachers and administrators with different levels of familiarity with the Ob3 platform.
This would cover the spectrum and yield some valuable insights and we're confident that Riri will have a whale of a time chatting with them since this is her forte.
Even if it's rather late, if the interview results come back early enough we may even be able to tweak or make some extra tables and queries and include them in our report/presentation.
For Rodney, it seems the project has just begun.
The sarcasm aside, I did feel encouraged to continue working on this project, perhaps in a different role.
Rodney himself has said that he would find some arrangement if anyone of us is interested.
Personally, I'm excited at the chance of being able to work with his developer, who actually used to be an intern at Ob3 back in 2011.
Just being able to observe the workflow or handling some small tasks like documenting or writing unit tests would be great.

And Rodney also said that his dev is too busy and costly to be involved in technical exploration, something that our project is definitely about, so I'm willing to do that, even if it means getting on a more intimate terms with Cassandra.
Plus, based on what Rodney's revealed about the future direction their platform is taking, chances are I may get to see server-side React and GraphQL in action as well.
Now that the detour has finished, let me list all the problems that happened when I tried to deploy our notebook to Heroku: .
- The build fails until I realized winpy32 is Window-specific and does not run on Docker Linux.
- Our notebook some how got The kernel language field wrong in its metadata.
- Tornado.py doesn't work with some Window policy.
- We still can't configure Jupyter notebook to run the setup cell first before others, so we need to copy paste all the imports in every code cell for now.
- Heroku doesn't recognize Window's path since it uses Docker Linux.
After hard-coding some if-else statement, I realized that there's the convenient built-in os.path.join() in Python.
- Plotly sometimes show a blank instead of a chart, and it takes either a refresh or some weird trick like trying to download The plot image to make it work.
Still, it's up there now and feel free to visit our notebook at : Â https: //ob3-data-modelling-report.herokuapp.com/.
Just like week 2, I've overcome my fear of diving into the lib packages and obscure discussion threads while bug-fixing.
But I also feel the agony of incompatibility during deployment, and I kind of know why such things as npm, Python virtual environment, virtual machine and Docker exist.
As such, I would like to get the hang of these deployment techniques in future projects.

Give that next week's the last leg of the race, I will focus on refining the outline and content of our online report so that it makes sense to various audiences, especially those who are not used to Cassandra and Ob3.
Of course, technical discussions will still be as in-depth as we can since Rodney and probably his dev are our main audience as well.
Hopefully our team will be able to strike a balance.
The second and equally obvious goal is to start working on my individual report.
It's been a wide ride and it's a nice opportunity to look back and derive some general lessons from it all.
Overall
